<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06250047 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06250047 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: New York Post; EVERYTHING STOLEN -- Steve and Lynette Holroydhad to wear hospital garb after their car and rental trailer were stolen.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  MARRIAGE; BEGIN; FAMILY; NEW-YORK; TRIP; ROBBERY; VICTIM  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The rest of the world may think the Big Apple is rotten, but New Yorkers arechanging the minds of a woman from Fremont and her new husband.;   Oftenaccused of a callous, hard-boiled attitude, natives of the City That NeverSleeps have been touched by the plight of newlyweds Steve and Lynette Holroyd,who had all their possessions ripped off less than 12 hours after they arrivedin New York.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  'FOR RICHER -- NOW POORER'VICTIMIZED NEWLYWEDS SEE SHINE ON BIG APPLE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;All we had were the clothes on our back,&quot; Steve said Thursday.;   One ofthe city's famed tabloids, the New York Post, gave their story front pagecoverage with headlines that blared &quot;Honeymoon's Over -- Because It WasStolen&quot; and &quot;For Richer -- Now Poorer.&quot; And offers of help started rollingin.;   Married July 28, the Holroyds arrived Monday night in the New York Cityborough of Brooklyn, where Steve Holroyd was to start as a third-year medicalstudent at 473-bed Coney Island Hospital. The next morning they parked theircar and rental trailer outside the hospital.;   When they returned, the carand trailer were gone. Although the vehicles were later found, they wereempty. Adding to their dismay was the fact that Steve Holroyd had all of hispossessions stolen on his only other excursion to the city three yearsearlier.;   The first Post story hit the streets Wednesday. Eager to showthere is a heart at the core of their metropolis, New Yorkers responded withgenerosity. The Holroyds have been flooded with offers of help -- free motelrooms, furniture, money, clothes.;   &quot;One person offered us a three-bedroomhouse with six months' free rent,&quot; Steve said, &quot;but that was about a half-houraway&quot; from the hospital.;   Bill Hoffman, a New York Post reporter, said everyNew Yorker expects to be mugged sometime, but the natives get riled when thesame thing happens to visitors.;   &quot;Generally when the Post runs a Page 1story about a sad sack couple who get robbed in New York, people here goberserk because they don't want to think of New York as a miserable, rottenplace to live.&quot;;   The generosity hasn't stopped with New York. The ArubaTourist Bureau has offered them a free honeymoon in the Caribbean vacationspot. When they get a chance, they plan to take it.;   Shattered by theexperience on her first visit to New York, Lynette Holroyd, who was born inCastro Valley and grew up in the East Bay, may go home.;   She and herhusband, a San Francisco native who was reared in Lafayette, are being treatedto a free motel room near the hospital as they sift through the offers ofhelp, deciding which ones to accept. They plan to refuse donations that areimpractical, but &quot;we're contacting everybody and at least saying thanks,&quot;Steve Holroyd said.;   The experience made him realizing that while &quot;there'squite a bit of filth around New York . . . there are nice things, too.&quot;;  However, when Steve's schooling is finished, the couple hope to move back tothe Bay Area, even though he says &quot;it's growing so much it's becoming less andless appealing and more like . . . &quot; -- he chooses his words carefully -- &quot;LosAngeles.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  DENNIS AKIZUKI, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910906  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  559  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday, September 6, 199100250047,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENGFRONT  </LANGUAGE></DOC>